<sec id="sec015" class="sec">
 <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Support for mitigation and adaptation policies</div>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Attitudes and sceptical beliefs (Model 1) did the best job of explaining people’s 
  <span class="italic">support for mitigation policies</span> (
  <span class="italic">R</span>
  <span class="sup">
   <span class="italic">2</span>
  </span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">adjusted</span>
  </sub> =. 37 /. 54, 
  <a rid="pone.0124843.t002" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0124843.t002">Table 2</a>): The more positive people’s attitude towards nature and the stronger their attitude to protect the environment (Switzerland) or to address climate change (UK) and the less they were sceptical about climate change, the more they were willing to support mitigation policies. (Analytical) risk perceptions (proximal and distant risks) represented the second most powerful predictor of mitigation support—as can be seen in the amount of variance explained as a separate predictor block (
  <span class="italic">R</span>
  <span class="sup">
   <span class="italic">2</span>
  </span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">adjusted</span>
  </sub> =. 29 /. 37, Model 3, 
  <a rid="pone.0124843.t002" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0124843.t002">Table 2</a>) and the size of their Beta-weights in the Full Models (
  <a rid="pone.0124843.t002" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0124843.t002">Table 2</a>).
 </p>
